  ],
  title: 'Incorrect verb form',
  minicardTitle: 'Change the verb form',
  result: '',
  details: '<p>A singular subject requires a singular verb, and a plural subject requires a plural verb. When there is a lot of text between the subject and the verb, it’s easy to lose track of which words need to agree. When you need to determine what the subject is, it’s often helpful to ask who or what is “doing” the action of the verb. It’s possible for the word <i>there</i> to stand in as a grammatical subject, as in sentences such as <i>There is a pie on the table</i> or <i>There are forks in the drawer.</i> In this type of construction, the verb is controlled not by the word <i>there</i> but by the logical subject of the clause, which usually comes right after the verb.\n',
  explanation: '<p>The verb <b>do</b> does not seem to agree with the subject <b>the implementation</b>. Consider changing the verb form.\n',
  examples: '<p><span class="red">Incorrect: I hope this message <b>find</b> you well.</span><br/><span class="green">Correct: I hope this message <b>finds</b> you well.</span><br/><p><span class="red">Incorrect: The book, including all the chapters in the first section, <b>are</b> boring.</span><br/><span class="green">Correct: The book, including all the chapters in the first section, <b>is</b> boring.</span><br/>',
  todo: 'change the verb form',
  handbookLink: '',
  sentence_no: 0,
  free: true,
